Real World Application: High-Concurrency Order Processing

Imagine an e-commerce website.

When a user places an order, many things happen:

1 User Order Request
        │
        ▼
1. Save Order
2. Check Inventory
3. Payment Processing
4. Send Email
5. Notify Delivery Service

Each of these tasks may involve I/O operations (database, API calls).

With traditional threads this can consume many resources.

With Virtual Threads (introduced in Java 21), we can handle thousands of requests efficiently.

Project Structure (Spring Boot)

Using Spring Boot

src/main/java
│
├── controller
│     OrderController
│
├── service
│     OrderService
│
└── config
      VirtualThreadConfig
1️⃣ Virtual Thread Configuration
package com.example.config;

import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;

import java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService;
import java.util.concurrent.Executors;

@Configuration
public class VirtualThreadConfig {

    @Bean
    public ExecutorService virtualExecutor() {
        return Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor();
    }
}

Here every task runs on a virtual thread.

2️⃣ Order Service
package com.example.service;

import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

import java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService;

@Service
public class OrderService {

    private final ExecutorService executor;

    public OrderService(ExecutorService executor) {
        this.executor = executor;
    }

    public void processOrder(String orderId) {

        executor.submit(() -> checkInventory(orderId));
        executor.submit(() -> processPayment(orderId));
        executor.submit(() -> sendEmail(orderId));
        executor.submit(() -> notifyDelivery(orderId));
    }

    private void checkInventory(String orderId) {
        System.out.println("Checking inventory for " + orderId +
                " Thread: " + Thread.currentThread());
    }

    private void processPayment(String orderId) {
        System.out.println("Processing payment for " + orderId +
                " Thread: " + Thread.currentThread());
    }

    private void sendEmail(String orderId) {
        System.out.println("Sending email for " + orderId +
                " Thread: " + Thread.currentThread());
    }

    private void notifyDelivery(String orderId) {
        System.out.println("Notifying delivery for " + orderId +
                " Thread: " + Thread.currentThread());
    }
}

Each task runs concurrently using virtual threads.

3️⃣ Controller
package com.example.controller;

import com.example.service.OrderService;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/orders")
public class OrderController {

    private final OrderService orderService;

    public OrderController(OrderService orderService) {
        this.orderService = orderService;
    }

    @PostMapping("/{id}")
    public String placeOrder(@PathVariable String id) {

        orderService.processOrder(id);

        return "Order placed successfully";
    }
}
How It Works

User sends request:

POST /orders/101

Execution flow:

Request
   │
   ▼
OrderController
   │
   ▼
OrderService
   │
   ▼
Virtual Threads
   │ │ │ │
   ▼ ▼ ▼ ▼
Inventory Payment Email Delivery

All tasks run in parallel.

Why Virtual Threads Help

Without virtual threads:

10,000 requests
=
10,000 platform threads

Memory problem.

With virtual threads:

10,000 requests
=
10,000 virtual threads
=
Only ~10 platform threads internally

Much more scalable.

Where Virtual Threads Are Used in Real Systems

Web servers

API gateways

Microservices

Database calls

External API calls

They are especially useful for I/O heavy applications.

Interview One-Line Answer

Virtual threads can be used in high-concurrency systems like e-commerce order processing, where thousands of requests perform I/O operations concurrently without consuming large system resources.
